# Code quality

- Prefer clear, typed, boring code.
- Make invalid states hard to represent.
- Handle errors explicitly at system boundaries: IO, network calls, database calls, parsing, authentication, permissions, and user input.
- Avoid catching errors only to suppress them.
- Keep functions small enough to test directly.
- Prefer composition over inheritance unless the existing codebase already uses inheritance for the relevant pattern.
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions. Add an abstraction only after there are at least two concrete uses or a clear stability boundary.
- Do not add comments that merely repeat the code. Add comments only for non-obvious business logic, tradeoffs, workarounds, or external constraints.
- Prefer existing project conventions over generic best practices.
